  footnotes: []
english:
  title: 'Hearing the Guqin: Harmonizing with Scholar Chen Hwa''s Verse'
  author: Lee Gyeongbo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Human heart and guqin strings—by fortune they blend in subtle accord,
    Finger and fiber meet each other with perfect ease.
    The ancient spirit breathes forth; my mind grows ever clearer,
    Communing with immortals, my very bones turn light.

    Clearer than spring water falling on distant rocks,
    Deeper than wind stirring in the hidden valley below.
    When the music fades, the moon has tilted in its course,
    And my spirit, washed and crystalline, emerges anew.
  footnotes:
    - The guqin (거문고 in Korean) is an ancient stringed instrument with profound spiritual and philosophical significance in East Asian culture, often associated with refinement, immortality, and communion with nature.
    - The poem employs the regulated verse form with rhyming couplets, responding to Scholar Chen Hwa's original composition—a common practice among literati of the Goryeo period.
